Now I notice something interesting in the AIM_STILL case.

C code (line 1627-1635):
```c
if ((player_visibility == 2) || (previous_visibility == 2)) {
    if (!ai_multiplayer_awareness(obj, 71)) {
        if (maybe_ai_do_actual_firing_stuff(obj, aip))
            ai_do_actual_firing_stuff(...);
        return;
    }
    ai_turn_towards_vector(&vec_to_player, obj, robptr->turn_time[Difficulty_level]);
    ai_multi_send_robot_position(objnum, -1);


}

do_firing_stuff(obj, player_visibility, &vec_to_player);
```

OCaml code (lines 2383-2391):
```ocaml
if !player_visibility = 2 || saved_prev_vis = 2
then (
    let ok = Effect.perform (Ai_multiplayer_awareness 71) in
    if not ok
    then maybe_fire_mp ()
    else Effect.perform (Ai_multi_send_robot_position (-1)));
do_firing_stuff ();
```

In C, when `player_visibility == 2 || previous_visibility == 2`, the code checks multiplayer awareness and either fires or sends position updates, then always calls the firing function. The OCaml version performs the same awareness check but structures the logic differently with effects, still ending with the firing call.

Comparing the two: the C version returns early on awareness failure, while the OCaml version calls `maybe_fire_mp()` instead—I need to verify whether that function raises an exception to match the early exit behavior, since the OCaml code doesn't explicitly return like C does.

